# stop-reassess-gate-bulk-transformation — History

## v1.1.0 (2026-05-18)

**Changed by:** Session learning — skill-corpus consolidation (1,100 → 690 skills, 17 merge clusters)
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed

- Added new trigger condition (7): multi-wave merge/delete where Wave M manifests reference files deleted by Wave N
- Added new `When to Use` bullet for multi-wave scenarios
- Extended generalise list to include multi-wave skill-corpus merge
- Added new subsection `### Skill-merge variant: post-deletion re-grade` with Python recipe for dropping moot absorbed_skills entries and the 25%-MOOT-NOW threshold heuristic
- Added 2 new Failed Attempts rows: (a) trusting overlap-free manifests to also be deletion-free; (b) skipping Gate 2 because Wave 1 looked tight
- Added multi-wave data table to Results & Parameters (Wave 1/2/3 cluster counts, pct_lost, MOOT-NOW flags)
- Added second Verified On row: ProjectMnemosyne 2026-05-18 consolidation session
- Updated Overview date to 2026-05-18, Outcome to summarize both sessions
- Added `history` frontmatter field pointing to this file
- Updated tags: added multi-wave, skill-merge, post-deletion

### Why

The gate pattern was validated a second time at a larger scale (skill-corpus consolidation
with 17 merge clusters across 3 waves, ~1,100 → 690 skills). The session surfaced a
refinement: overlap-resolution at Gate 1 prevents Wave-N-vs-Wave-N collisions but does NOT
prevent Wave-N file deletions from invalidating Wave-M manifests. The post-deletion re-grade
step is always cheap and never skippable.

Observed data: only M3 (Mojo) lost 4 members (4%) after Wave 1 — well below the 25%
MOOT-NOW threshold. All other 7 Wave 2/3 clusters lost 0 members, confirming that the
Gate 1 overlap-resolution step prevents most cross-wave invalidation.

